s affected the brain and the person’s ability to breath. Breathing can slow down to dangerously low levels and in some cases even stop. Recognizing when someone has overdosed can be the difference between life or death.\n\nPotential signs of an opioid overdose:\n<ul>\n<li>Person will not wake up or respond to you when you call their name or when you touch them</li>\n<li>Breathing is irregular or extremely slow. Average person will breath at least every 5 seconds</ul>\n<li>Pupils (the dark circle in our eye) is small</ul>\n<li>Fingernail or lips turning blue. This is a sign that the body is not getting enough oxygen.</ul>\n<li>Body is limp and person is unable to move</ul>\n<l>Choking sound or a gurgling sound</ul>\n<ul>Unable to feel a pulse\n</ul>','Naloxone','','inherit','closed','closed','','89-autosave-v1','','','2018-04-28 19:54:32','2018-04-28 19:54:32','',89,'http://18.219.193.133/2018/04/28/89-autosave-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(139,2,'2018-04-28 20:50:25','2018-04-28 20:50:25','During an opioid overdose, the drug has affected the brain and the person’s ability to breath. Breathing can slow down to dangerously low levels and in some cases even stop. Recognizing when someone has overdosed can be the difference between life or death.\r\n\r\nPotential signs of an opioid overdose:<ul>\r\n<li>Person will not wake up or respond to you when you call their name or when you touch them</li>\r\n<li>Breathing is irregular or extremely slow. Average person will breath at least every 5 seconds</li>\r\n<li>Pupils (the dark circle in our eye) is small</li>\r\n<li>Fingernail or lips turning blue. This is a sign that the body is not getting enough oxygen.</li>\r\n<li>Body is limp and person is unable to move</li>\r\n<li>Choking sound or a gurgling sound</li>\r\n<li>Unable to feel a pulse</li>\r\n</ul>','Overdose Recognition','','publish','closed','closed','','overdose-recognition','','','2018-04-28 20:53:09','2018-04-28 20:53:09','',0,'http://18.219.193.133/?page_id=139',0,'pag